 but not high enough that consecutive tasks are fully automated (<1|2><3>,
 or <1><2|3>,
 or <1|2|3>).
 Mathematically:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\forall i\in\{1,2,3\}:\frac{c_{m}}{q_{i}}<c_{h}
\]

\end_inset

but
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C\{<1><2><3>\}=c_{m}(\frac{1}{q_{1}}+\frac{1}{q_{2}}+\frac{1}{q_{3}}) & <c_{m}\left(\frac{1}{q_{1}q_{2}}+\frac{1}{q_{3}}\right)=C\{<1|2><3>\},\\
C\{<1><2><3>\}=c_{m}(\frac{1}{q_{1}}+\frac{1}{q_{2}}+\frac{1}{q_{3}}) & <c_{m}\left(\frac{1}{q_{1}}+\frac{1}{q_{2}q_{3}}\right)=C\{<1><2|3>\},\\
C\{<1><2><3>\}=c_{m}(\frac{1}{q_{1}}+\frac{1}{q_{2}}+\frac{1}{q_{3}}) & <\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}q_{2}q_{3}}=C\{<1|2|3>\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now imagine 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 experiences a positive shock so that it increases from 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{q}_{2}>q_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We want to see if it is possible to move from <1><2><3> to 
\begin_inset Formula $<1|2>(3)$
\end_inset

 before eventually entering the full automation region.
 For this to happen the post-shock value must satisfy:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C\{<1><2><3>\} & >C\{<1|2>(3)\}\\
\Leftrightarrow\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}}+\frac{c_{m}}{\hat{q}_{2}}+\frac{c_{m}}{q_{3}} & >\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}}+c_{h}\\
\Leftrightarrow\underbrace{\frac{c_{m}}{q_{3}}-c_{h}}_{\text{cost advantage of task 3 done by machine}} & >\underbrace{c_{m}(\frac{1}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}}-\frac{1}{q_{1}}-\frac{1}{\hat{q}_{2}})}_{\text{cost advantage of switching from <1><2> to <1|2>}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

while
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C\{<1|2>(3)\}=\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}}+c_{h} & <c_{m}\left(\frac{1}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}}+\frac{1}{q_{3}}\right)=C\{<1|2><3>\},\\
C\{<1|2>(3)\}=\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}}+c_{h} & <c_{m}\left(\frac{1}{q_{1}}+\frac{1}{\hat{q}_{2}q_{3}}\right)=C\{<1><2|3>\},\\
C\{<1|2>(3)\}=\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}}+c_{h} & <\frac{c_{m}}{q_{1}\hat{q}_{2}q_{3}}=C\{<1|2|3>\}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This means that such a transitioning from machine back to human is possible if the cost advantage of fully automating 1 and 2 more than offsets the cost disadvantage of switching from <3> to (3).
